  "description": {
    "en": "Understand asyncio, coroutines, the event loop, and how async/await enables concurrent I/O without multi-threading.",
    "ta": "asyncio, coroutines, event loop, async/await எவ்வாறு multi-threading இல்லாமல் ஒருங்கிணைந்த I/O-ஐ இயக்குகிறது என்பதை புரிந்துகொள்ளுங்கள்."
  },
  "xp_reward": 75,
  "story_variants": {
    "en": "## Vaathiyaar's Restaurant Kitchen\n\nVaathiyaar becomes a chef. \"In a regular kitchen, you wait for water to boil before doing ANYTHING else. In an **async kitchen**, while water boils, you chop vegetables and prepare sauce. That's `async/await` — doing other work while waiting for I/O!\"\n\n### Sync vs Async\n\n| Sync | Async |\n|------|-------|\n| Wait for each task to finish | Start task, do other work while waiting |\n| `time.sleep(2)` blocks everything | `await asyncio.sleep(2)` lets others run |\n| One thing at a time | Concurrent I/O operations |\n\n### Key Concepts\n\n```python\nimport asyncio\n\nasync def fetch_data():      # coroutine function\n    await asyncio.sleep(1)   # non-blocking wait\n    return 'data'\n\nasyncio.run(fetch_data())    # start the event loop\n```\n\n| Term | Meaning |\n|------|----------|\n| `async def` | Defines a coroutine function |\n| `await` | Pause here, let other tasks run |\n| `asyncio.run()` | Start the event loop |\n| Event loop | Scheduler that manages coroutines |\n\n> **Key Concept:** `async/await` is NOT parallelism. It's **concurrency** — one thread doing multiple I/O-bound tasks by switching between them while waiting. Use threads/processes for CPU-bound work."
  },
